12 Sep 2015: IMF chief urges Africa to spend responsibly
http://www.seychellesnewsagency.com/articles/3697/IMF+chief+urges+Africa+to+spend+responsibly
[IMF [International Monetary Fund] chief, Christine Lagarde, urged African governments to spend responsibly as she visited Liberia on Fri [11 Sep 2015], a week after it was declared free from the Ebola virus disease (EVD) epidemic which has shattered its economy. Lagarde, wrapping up 2 days of meetings with President Ellen Johnson Sirleaf, business leaders and community activists, set out measures she said were necessary "for African governments to be financially disciplined." "I would say that for the economy to prosper, and to be seen as prospering, having sound and reliable data is certainly a condition," she told journalists in the capital Monrovia. "2nd, not to be overburdened, and [3rd], make sure that public spending and public finance, is deployed in the most growth-friendly fashion," Lagarde told journalists... - more]

10 Sep 2015: Kenya: African scientists funded to seek cures for AIDS, Ebola at home
http://www.trust.org/item/20150910164902-6c68v/
[An African research fund launched in Kenya on Thu 10 Sep 2015 aims to raise the quality of Africa's scientific output and tackle diseases primarily affecting the world's poorest continent, such as HIV/AIDS, malaria and Ebola [Ebola virus disease, EVD]. The Alliance for Accelerating Excellence in Science in Africa (AESA), based at the African Academy of Sciences in the Kenyan capital Nairobi, aims to draw increased funding from the West and African governments to set up centers of scientific excellence on the continent. "What AESA hopes to achieve is to look at the major diseases that are already epidemics, the neglected tropical diseases ... and the emerging challenges like Ebola, and really build the capacities to try to deal with these challenges," AESA Director Tom Kariuki told the Thomson Reuters Foundation. Scientists funded by AESA will work towards creating new vaccines, products and services for diseases that primarily affect Africans.

On Thu [19 Sep 2015], the Alliance for Accelerating Excellence in Science in Africa (AESA) announced a grant of USD 70 million to support 7 African researchers working on issues such as mental health in Zimbabwe, HIV/AIDS and tuberculosis in South Africa and malaria in Mali... - more]

11 Sep 2015 Liberia: UNDP provides USD 362 500 for a community project
http://en.starafrica.com/news/liberia-undp-provides-362-500-for-community-project.html
[A check of USD 362 500, funded through the Ebola Multi-Partners Trust Fund (MPTF), has been awarded to Mother Patten College by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP), according to a UNDP press statement issued here on Friday [11 Sep 2015]. This fund would help implement the Community Quick Impact Project (C-QIP) initially managed by the United Nations Mission for Ebola Emergency Response (UNMEER) within the framework of its Ebola Response Quick Impact Projects (ERQIPs). The project is expected to benefit up to 70 Community-based-organizations (CBOs) in Montserrado County, which will receive micro-grants of up to USD 5000 based on vetted, but simple, proposals supporting small-scale, low-cost community-empowerment projects... - more]

11 Sep 2015 Liberia: Ministers, agencies face audits
http://allafrica.com/stories/201509110462.html
[Several ministries and agencies, including a commission, are to face auditing to give account of money [entrusted] to their care for various projects for which they had self-disbursing authority. President Ellen Johnson-Sirleaf, in a statement released on Thu [10 Sep 2015], urged the General Auditing Commission [GAC] to consider private auditing firms to conduct urgent audits into the activities of these ministries and agencies under her direct supervision. ...- more]

